english:
  title: A Record of the Pavilion of Emerald Clouds
  author: An Chuk
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the spring of the Huangqing year of Renzi, I rode forth alone to wander through Seonsa Province. South of the province, upon a bank of white sand, stood several thousand young pine trees, their branches and leaves abundant and pleasing to the eye. Turning to my companion from the town, I spoke: 'When these pines have grown tall, should we build a pavilion here, it would rival the Hall of Cold Pines and the Pavilion of the Distant Pines.' After that time, whenever townspeople came to visit me, they would surely ask after the well-being of those trees.

    Many years later, during the Taiding era in the year of Bingyin, I heard that Minister Park, the Prefect of Stability and Care, had constructed a new tower in Seonsa Province with the most graceful design. When I inquired about its location, I discovered it was precisely where I had once seen those tender saplings. For years I harbored the desire to ascend this tower and fulfill my long-forgotten wish, yet circumstances never permitted it. Now, by fortune's grace, having come to govern this region, I have returned to climb this tower again. Its crystalline tranquility and sublime beauty surpass anything one encounters in the tumultuous world of men.

    Indeed, towers and pavilions are built in one of two ways: either in lofty, open expanses or in quiet, secluded depths. When one tires of the former, one longs for the latter; when one wearies of the latter, one dreams of the former—such is the nature of the human heart. All the towers and pavilions of the eastern regions stand in high, open places, so that visitors find their eyes exhausted by raging waves and their bodies drained by thick mists. Yet upon ascending this tower and encountering its serene, secluded beauty, one feels as a hunted beast fleeing into a hidden valley feels, or as a weary bird returning to a dense forest feels—there dwells the greatest joy. Is this not Minister Park's intent in constructing this tower?

    Minister Park possesses noble refinement and penetrating wisdom far beyond my humble and crude understanding. Yet in his creation of this tower, his vision happened to accord with my shallow observations of long ago. Should any wonder that I possess discernment in recognizing such marvels and exceptional places? Reflecting now upon those old journeys, twenty-four years have passed, and those tender saplings have all grown tall and strong. When one has seen pines in their youth and then beholds them in their maturity, how can the heart remain unmoved? Overwhelmed by this bittersweet remembrance, I cannot pass in silence, and so I write this record.
  footnotes:
    - Huangqing (皇慶) was an era name in Yuan dynasty; Renzi (壬子) refers to the year 1312.
    - The reference to 'Hall of Cold Pines' and 'Pavilion of the Distant Pines' alludes to famous literary structures, suggesting the author's pavilion would be worthy of comparison.
    - Taiding (泰定) was another Yuan era; Bingyin (丙寅) refers to 1326, indicating approximately 24 years had passed between the author's visits.
    - The author is contrasting the stark, exposed beauty of typical eastern pavilions with the sheltered, intimate beauty of this particular tower—a philosophical meditation on complementary aesthetic experiences.
